current.title: Year in Review: 1969
current.description: Year in Review: 1969. The Cleveland Museum of Art (January 27-February 22, 1970).

assets.wall_description: The hei-tiki is a stylized human figure with head tilted to one side, hands on hips, and feet tucked under the body.  The face wears a wide-eyed expression, and has a broad mouth with a defiantly protruding tongue.  Because greenstone was considered a supernatural substance, hei-tikis carved from it became family heirlooms.  Their intrinsic value, or mana, increased as they passed from one generation to the next.  During his voyages to the South Pacific, Captain James Cook collected a number of these neck pendants.  In 1769 he gave one to King George III of England, which remains in the collection of the royal family.

assets.wall_description: The wahaika, carried in a belt, was used by the Maori in hand-to-hand combat.  Early, undecorated clubs were made of stone.  Bone and wood clubs were decorated with increasingly complex carved designs.  The small figure clinging to the side of this club may well represent the supernatural power (mana) of the weapon, while the face at the end of the grip expresses the aggression of combat.

assets.tombstone: Ceremonial Adze, 1800s. Polynesia, Mangaia, Cook Islands, 19th century. Wood, stone, fiber; overall: 10.2 cm (4 in.); blade: 9.3 x 3.6 cm (3 11/16 x 1 7/16 in.). The Cleveland Museum of Art, Gift of Richard Inglis 1940.1078
assets.title: Ceremonial Adze
assets.department: Oceania
assets.measurements: Overall: 10.2 cm (4 in.); Blade: 9.3 x 3.6 cm (3 11/16 x 1 7/16 in.)
assets.wall_description: Before European contact, Polynesian carving tools were fashioned from bone, shell, stone, or teeth. The introduction of iron tools facilitated carving, while the demand of European sailors and missionaries for souvenirs provided a new market for craft products. Ceremonial adzes probably represented gods or spirits. The wooden handle of this example is carved with the characteristic K motif. The stone adze blade is lashed to the handle with finely plaited sennit fiber cord. According to legend, the distinctive pattern formed by the sennit lashing was taught to Mangaian craftsman by the gods.

assets.wall_description: Intricate surface patterning characterizes Maori wood carvings.  The swirls and spirals covering the face on this canoe prow replicate traditional facial tattoo patterns.  Similar designs were used for post and gable figures that adorned both dwellings and compounds.

citations.citation: Sims, Lowery Stokes. The Persistence of Geometry: Form, Content, and Culture in the Collection of the Cleveland Museum of Art. Cleveland: Cleveland Museum of Art, 2006.

current.title: Year in Review (1963)
current.description: Year in Review (1963). The Cleveland Museum of Art (organizer) (November 26, 1963-January 5, 1964).

assets.wall_description:
The Maori positioned carved lintels above the doorways of their large meeting houses.  The central figure (tiki), with legs in the war dance pose and tongue stuck out in defiance of the enemy, is flanked on either side by profile figures called manaia.  These creatures may represent either evil spirits or the spiritual power (mana) of the central tiki.

     The carving of a lintel is accomplished in three stages by skilled specialists.  First, the outline of the design is carved into the wood; next, the design is carved in deeper relief.  Finally, the decorative symbols and spirals indicating the joints in the legs and arms are added.  Often the carving is colored with red ochre, and shell eyes may be included.
